subSubSection.paragraph:
Diagnosis.

P. semicruciata

belongs to the species, in which the male subgenital plate has two medium sized to small internal processes in basal quarter to half and the apex of the cercus is simply obtuse. It differs from the other species with the same characters by the ventral baso-internal process inserting distinctly closer to base than the dorsal process (
Fig. 212
), the apico-internal process of the cercus being compressed with a short dorsal lamella at base (
Figs. 142–143
), and the apical parts of the titillators being oval with the apex obliquely truncate (
Figs. 304, 309
). Females are characterised by the subgenital plate being divided in midline by a membranous area; the lobes are in ventral view nearly Y-shaped with a small median expansion; the basal area is sloping, the proximal surface is deeply furrowed and the lateral surface shallowly grooved; the apex of the lobes is obtuse (
Figs. 446–447
).
